title: Updates based on feedback from afrind@ and kazuhooku@.
body:
Hi Mike.  I have some updates based on e-mail responses to the -04 draft.

afrind@ requested various clarifications.

kazuhooku@ pointed out that prefix is not required for the control stream, since order there is guaranteed.

title: Drop mandatory de-duplication and simplify prefix.
body:
Simplify QCRAM for now.  Can add these back later if wins are
demonstrated.

title: Ack on control
body:
(Builds on #3; ignore changes introduced by that commit.)

The current HEADER_ACK frame doesn't actually work in HTTP/QUIC, since it requires being sent on the same stream on which the header block was received.  In the case of server response headers, the client has already closed the stream; in the case of server push streams, the stream is unidirectional.

This changes the HEADER_ACK to be sent on the control stream and use the variable-length encoding used by other HTTP/QUIC frames.  (I considered using an HPACK 8-bit prefix integer, but that requires reading one byte at a time to find the end of the frame.  The length of a QUIC varint can be determined immediately from the first byte, which is somewhat preferable.)

title: Editorial pass
body:
Since we're strongly considering this as the direction we want to go technically, I did an editorial pass over the document in hopes of making it more readable for a broader audience.  I don't think I've changed anything normative here, except that I made it a SHOULD to minimize references to old entries.

Feel free to revert or further edit anything you don't like, obviously.

(I did have one technical change I'd like to suggest, but I'll do that separately.)

title: Control stream
body:
I think the minimal changes for this are actually really simple -- add restrictions on what can be sent on/off control stream and remove the reset recovery pieces.  There's text cleanup and discussion that can be done later.

Becomes much more readable if #1 is merged first; otherwise, look specifically at the last commit.
